Engagement in Free-Fall: Why SAP Community Blogs Struggle to Be Seen

Marian Zeis

Independent SAP Consultant and Developer
13. Mai 2025

Back in April 2024 I opened this little series with From Open Exchange to Corporate Monologue, followed in August by SAP Community in Decline and, just before Christmas, the GPT-assisted look at question quality. Twelve months, two platform releases and several batch-downloads later it is time for round four this time with a split focus:

  • Who is writing the blog posts today?
  • Does anybody still read them?

1 | Share of SAP vs. Non-SAP Blog Posts Little News on the Macro Level

Nothing has changed was my gut feeling and the long-range chart confirms it. Since the second half of 2023 the SAP share hovers stubbornly between 60 % and 70 %; no new record highs, but also no real retreat.


Does the plateau invalidate my earlier alarm?

Not really. The community never bounced back to the sub-40 % employee share we enjoyed a decade ago the status-quo is simply frozen at a two-thirds corporate voice.

Assumption check: My earlier claim of no further change holds for percentages, but the green bars (absolute SAP posts) are still inching up. The non-SAP bars are mostly flat. So the balance only stays constant because both lines move in parallel.

2 | Tech-Blog Boards A Very Different Story

Drill down to the two technology boards (technology-blog-sap, technology-blog-members) and you get a much livelier picture.

Key observations:

  1. Member posts are growing up by ~25 % year-on-year.
  2. SAP posts are shrinking down by ~15 % in the same period (escpecially 2025-01 to 2025-03).

Assumption:

The main reason for this change is the lower number of SAP blog posts.One possible explanation is that the personal target number of blog posts required to achieve a possible bonus has been reached. This also explains the high number of SAP blog posts in December.

There was also an increase in blog posts from non-SAP members and new members of the SAP community (see next point).

3 | Who Are Those Members? Rank Distribution


The green bars (Participant +) show a drop to barely 40 % in February before recovering to the mid-40s. Net-net the fresh content boom is fuelled primarily by new contributors.

Additional assumption: A steady inflow of first-time authors is great if their pieces are curated and converted into repeat contributions. Otherwise we risk a drive-by blogging pattern that never matures (see next point about views).

4 | Views The Elephant in the Room

When SAP switched the platform to Khoros I planned to ignore the view counter until the time-series smacked me in the face:

The trajectory is crystal-clear:

  • Sharp decline since 2020, long before the migration.
  • Mean > median a few viral posts keep the average alive; the typical post is doing much worse.

Are the counters reliable?

I have already written that I do not consider the view parameters to be reliable. However, I cannot ignore this chart because the trend is quite clear.I trust the trend because it reflects my personal feeling.

I strongly suspect that the curve is not so extreme in real numbers, but only SAP itself can answer this question with its own analytics data.

But if you look at the number of posts here, there is no downward trend. This confirms my impression that a lot of blog posts are written by non-SAP members and that SAP employees are encouraged to write blog posts.

This combination automatically leads to a decline in quality and therefore in engagement, which confirms my impression that blog posts that are really worth reading are becoming rarer.

6 | What Could SAP (and We) Do?

This is a difficult question to answer because there is no simple answer. Platform migration is only part of the answer, because engagement was already declining before that, but it definitely plays a big role.

If you look at the latest 'What's New' post from the SAP community, the bug fixes are ones that shouldn't have been there in the first place and are just minor cosmetic changes. It doesn't change the big picture. And now, years after the migration, I don't see any quick changes and we have to deal with the current situation.

As a community, there's nothing we can do about it, because you can't build a community of this size 'overnight' - there are legal requirements that can't be met with a small team.

Bjrn Schulz is doing a great job with his website and excellent content: https://software-heroes.com/

As Twitter is dying and Bluesky can't take its place, the only alternative so far is (unfortunately) LinkedIn. There's a lot of (at best) bad content there, but also a lot of untruths, and it's also flooded with AI content.

At the moment, my optimism about the SAP community has faded a bit. If anyone has any suggestions on how to reunite the community, I'm all ears!

Mike Zaschka 1.

Unabhngiger SAP Solution Architect, Entwickler & Berater
8 Monate
Thank you, Marian for this insightful overview. Its unfortunate to see the decline of the SAP Community, and I share your concernits hard to see a clear path to recovery. From my perspective, there isnt a single cause, but rather a mix of factors:

Improved access to knowledge: In the past, SAP-related documentation was scarce and/or expensive. Today, free online courses and tutorials have made learning more accessible, reducing reliance on a central community platform.

Platform usability issues: Writing and publishing content is often frustrating due to formatting problems and moderation hurdles. This discourages meaningful contributions.

Shift to alternative platforms: LinkedIn has become more and more the go-to space for SAP professionals to share insights, with greater visibility and engagement potential.

Strategic missteps: Frequent overhauls of the community platformchanging core structures like tags, feeds, and segregation of contenthave alienated long-time users. Constant reinvention without clear community/customer demand erodes trust.

Its a complex situation, but one that highlights the importance of listening to and evolving with the community. And SAP sadly failed here.
1 Antwort 1 Kommentar zu dem Kommentar von Mike Zaschka

Marian Zeis Autor:in

Independent SAP Consultant and Developer
8 Monate
Mike Zaschka I agree with all your points, and it's a real shame because all of these points are within SAP's control.
The SAP tutorials have shown that, with the will to do so, these issues can be improved and even made available free of charge.
With a good platform, there would probably still be a shift towards LinkedIn, but if the focus were on the aspects that the SAP community stands for, it would be possible to stand out from the competition.
The longer there is no focus, the less I see a bright future for the SAP Community website.

in Free-Fall: Why SAP Community Blogs Struggle to Be Seen","contentHtml":"<p>Back in April 2024 I opened this little series with <a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/from-open-exchange-corporate-monologue-transformation-marian-zeis-zu6xf/?trackingId=zlAJL9JjRSqoZGkFfmTkGQ%3D%3D\" target=\"_blank\"><em>From Open Exchange to Corporate Monologue</em></a>, followed in August by <a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/sap-community-decline-engagement-continues-fall-little-marian-zeis-1wvif/?trackingId=zlAJL9JjRSqoZGkFfmTkGQ%3D%3D\" target=\"_blank\"><em>SAP Community in Decline</em></a> and, just before Christmas, the GPT-assisted look at <a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/has-quality-sap-community-questions-gotten-worse-data-driven-zeis-bdyjf/?trackingId=zlAJL9JjRSqoZGkFfmTkGQ%3D%3D\" target=\"_blank\">question quality.</a> Twelve months, two platform releases and several batch-downloads later it is time for round four this time with a split focus:</p><ul><li><p><strong>Who is writing the blog posts today?</strong></p></li><li><p><strong>Does anybody still read them?</strong></p></li><li><p></p></li></ul><hr><h3>1 | Share of SAP vs. Non-SAP Blog Posts Little News on the Macro Level</h3><p>Nothing has changed was my gut feeling and the long-range chart confirms it. Since the second half of 2023 the SAP share hovers stubbornly between <strong>60 % and 70 %</strong>; no new record highs, but also no real retreat.</p><p></p><figure><img data-media-urn=\"\" data-li-src=\"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D4D12AQHGijMnqIYYcg/article-inline_image-shrink_1000_1488/B4DZbIsGANGwAQ-/0/1747123725255?e=1771459200&amp;v=beta&amp;t=5LxUMgJDhmGCjimW-uaPbshugIyz1N5qOW-pCoz0Vj0\" src=\"//:0\"><figcaption>Share and absolute numbers of all blog posts, 2003-05 2025-05</figcaption></figure><h3>Does the plateau invalidate my earlier alarm?</h3><p>Not really. The community never bounced back to the sub-40 % employee share we enjoyed a decade ago the <em>status-quo</em> is simply frozen at a two-thirds corporate voice.</p><p><em>Assumption check:</em> My earlier claim of <strong>no further change holds for percentages</strong>, but the green bars (absolute SAP posts) are still inching up. The non-SAP bars are mostly flat. So the balance only stays constant because both lines move in parallel.</p><hr><h3>2 | Tech-Blog Boards A Very Different Story</h3><p>Drill down to the two technology boards (technology-blog-sap, technology-blog-members) and you get a much livelier picture.</p><figure><img data-media-urn=\"\" data-li-src=\"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D4D12AQGQzWPPMsRcJQ/article-inline_image-shrink_1000_1488/B4DZbIsVs5GwAQ-/0/1747123789611?e=1771459200&amp;v=beta&amp;t=vysdtfril8isVWR6sLeiiq-X1VS1j-PTyqL6ipCNR0s\" src=\"//:0\"><figcaption><em>Figure 2 Share and absolute numbers in the tech blogs, entire history</em></figcaption></figure><figure><img data-media-urn=\"\" data-li-src=\"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D4D12AQHzqPADiFGGkQ/article-inline_image-shrink_1500_2232/B4DZbIsrPxGwAU-/0/1747123877664?e=1771459200&amp;v=beta&amp;t=IiONp3VNezo6O8hr4qaNHBAw_5G_uJ-ZF3SePIFpw_4\" src=\"//:0\"><figcaption>Figure 3 Same data, last 12 months</figcaption></figure><p>Key observations:</p><ol><li><p><strong>Member posts are growing</strong> up by ~25 % year-on-year.</p></li><li><p><strong>SAP posts are shrinking</strong> down by ~15 % in the same period (escpecially 2025-01 to 2025-03).</p></li></ol><p><em>Assumption:</em></p><p>The main reason for this change is the lower number of SAP blog posts.One possible explanation is that the personal target number of blog posts required to achieve a possible bonus has been reached. This also explains the high number of SAP blog posts in December.</p><p>There was also an increase in blog posts from non-SAP members and new members of the SAP community (see next point).</p><hr><h3>3 | Who Are Those Members? Rank Distribution</h3><p></p><figure><img data-media-urn=\"\" data-li-src=\"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D4D12AQHCeapxLz5X5A/article-inline_image-shrink_1500_2232/B4DZbItlJuG8AU-/0/1747124114574?e=1771459200&amp;v=beta&amp;t=2Efk0peMIe8sV2CPpt2U-qwSTiE1kzIo7uTYXrdagn8\" src=\"//:0\"><figcaption><em>Figure 4 Experienced vs. inexperienced share in the tech blogs, last 12 months</em></figcaption></figure><p>The green bars (Participant +) show a <strong>drop to barely 40 %</strong> in February before recovering to the mid-40s. Net-net the fresh content boom is fuelled primarily by <em>new</em> contributors.</p><p><em>Additional assumption:</em> A steady inflow of first-time authors is great <strong>if</strong> their pieces are curated and converted into repeat contributions. Otherwise we risk a drive-by blogging pattern that never matures (see next point about views).</p><hr><h3>4 | Views The Elephant in the Room</h3><p>When SAP switched the platform to Khoros I planned to ignore the view counter until the time-series smacked me in the face:</p><figure><img data-media-urn=\"\" data-li-src=\"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D4D12AQEqoH8c8dQGdQ/article-inline_image-shrink_1500_2232/B4DZbIuK5lG8AY-/0/1747124270596?e=1771459200&amp;v=beta&amp;t=IOVwdSfLnrtrZMF01R-qmkylA3WqMoX04I-N3ubGAsE\" src=\"//:0\"><figcaption><em>Figure 5 Mean / median views and engagement quality</em></figcaption></figure><p>The trajectory is crystal-clear:</p><ul><li><p><strong>Sharp decline since 2020</strong>, long before the migration.</p></li><li><p>Mean &gt; median a few viral posts keep the average alive; the <em>typical</em> post is doing much worse.</p></li></ul><h3>Are the counters reliable?</h3><p>I have already written that I do not consider the view parameters to be reliable. However, I cannot ignore this chart because the trend is quite clear.I trust the trend because it reflects my personal feeling.</p><p>I strongly suspect that the curve is not so extreme in real numbers, but only SAP itself can answer this question with its own analytics data.</p><figure><img data-media-urn=\"\" data-li-src=\"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D4D12AQFc8ZGes1bweA/article-inline_image-shrink_1500_2232/B4DZbIuchkG0AY-/0/1747124342098?e=1771459200&amp;v=beta&amp;t=plCg-Dlitb3UYUb6MLEnn6hK6c6Vrv0C7dUYHNU_eog\" src=\"//:0\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p>But if you look at the number of posts here, there is no downward trend. This confirms my impression that a lot of blog posts are written by non-SAP members and that SAP employees are encouraged to write blog posts.</p><p>This combination automatically leads to a decline in quality and therefore in engagement, which confirms my impression that blog posts that are really worth reading are becoming rarer.</p><hr><h3>6 | What Could SAP (and We) Do?</h3><p>This is a difficult question to answer because there is no simple answer. Platform migration is only part of the answer, because engagement was already declining before that, but it definitely plays a big role.</p><p>If you look at the latest <a href=\"https://community.sap.com/t5/what-s-new/enhancements-for-sap-community-march-2025/ba-p/14037208\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">'What's New' </a>post from the SAP community, the bug fixes are ones that shouldn't have been there in the first place and are just minor cosmetic changes. It doesn't change the big picture. And now, years after the migration, I don't see any quick changes and we have to deal with the current situation.</p><p>As a community, there's nothing we can do about it, because you can't build a community of this size 'overnight' - there are legal requirements that can't be met with a small team.</p><p><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/bjoern-schulz-swh?miniProfileUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afs_miniProfile%3AACoAAEAuA-8B110WSlPCiLlDjwSuL0_PY08wZzk\">Bjrn Schulz</a> is doing a great job with his website and excellent content: <a href=\"https://software-heroes.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">https://software-heroes.com/</a></p><p>As Twitter is dying and <a href=\"https://go.bsky.app/M3Q7Nng\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Bluesky</a> can't take its place, the only alternative so far is (unfortunately) LinkedIn. There's a lot of (at best) bad content there, but also a lot of untruths, and it's also flooded with AI content.</p><p>At the moment, my optimism about the SAP community has faded a bit.
